Part 1: Explore album sales

Part 1A:

Use lubridate to create a column called released that is a Date class. However, to be able to do this, you first need to use stringr to search for pattern that matches things like this â€œ(US)[51]â€ in a string like this â€œSeptember 1, 2006 (US)[51]â€ and removes them. (Note: to get full credit, you must create the regular expression). Use forcats to create a factor called country (Note: you may need to collapse some factor levels). Transform the sales into a unit that is album sales in millions of dollars. Keep only album sales from the UK, the US or the World. Auto print your final wrangled tibble data frame.

sales <- sales %>%
  mutate(released = str_remove(released, "\\s*\\(\\w+\\)\\[\\d+\\]"), released) %>% 
  mutate(released = as.Date(released, format = "%B %d, %Y"))%>% 
  mutate(album_sales_permil = sales/1000000) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "World", "WW", country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "FRA", "FR", country)) %>% 
  filter(country %in% c("UK", "US", "WW"))

country_levels<- c("US", "WW", "AUS", "UK", "JPN", "CAN", "FR") # World is changed to WW and FRA to FR
country<- factor(sales$country, levels = country_levels)

Part 1C

Using the wrangled data from Part 1A:

Calculate the total album sales for each artist and for each country (only sales from the UK, US, and World). Note: assume that the World sales do not include the UK and US ones. Using the total album sales, create a percent stacked barchart using ggplot2 of the percentage of sales of studio albums (in millions) along the y-axis for the two artists along the x-axis colored by the country.

total_sales <- sales %>%
  filter(artist %in% c("Taylor Swift", "BeyoncÃ©") & country %in% c("UK", "US", "WW")) %>%
  group_by(artist, country) %>%
  summarize(total_album_sales = sum(album_sales_permil))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'artist'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
total_sales <- total_sales %>%
  group_by(artist) %>%
  mutate(percentage = total_album_sales / sum(total_album_sales) * 100)
ggplot(total_sales, aes(x = artist, y = percentage, fill = country)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Artist", y = "Percentage of Sales", fill = "Country", title = "Percent Sales of Studio Albums in Millions") +
  theme_classic()

Only keep the top 25 most frequent words. Auto print the wrangled tibble data frame. Use ggplot2 to create a bar plot with the top words on the y-axis and the frequency of each word on the x-axis. Color each bar by the sentiment of each word from the â€œbingâ€ sentiment lexicon. Bars should be ordered from most frequent on the top to least frequent on the bottom of the plot. b_lyrics_tokens<- b_lyrics %>% 
  unnest_tokens(
    output = word,
    input = line,
    token = "words"

  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word")

Using the ts_lyrics dataset,

Tokenize each lyrical line by words. Remove the â€œstopwordsâ€. Calculate the total number for each word in the lyrics for each Album. Auto print the wrangled tibble data frame. Join the wrangled data frame from Part 1A (album sales in millions) filtered down to US sales with the wrangled data frame from #6 above (average sentiment score for each album). Using ggplot2, create a scatter plot of the average sentiment score for each album (y-axis) and the album release data along the x-axis. Make the size of each point the album sales in millions. Add a horizontal line at y-intercept=0. Write 2-3 sentences interpreting the plot answering the question â€œHow has the sentiment of Taylor Swiftâ€™s albums have changed over time?â€. Add a title, subtitle, and useful axis labels.

sentiments_afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn")
ts_afinn_album<- ts_lyrics %>% 
  unnest_tokens(
    output = word,
    input = line,
    token = "words"
  ) %>% anti_join(stop_words) %>% group_by(Album) %>% count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>% summarise(Album = Album, avg_sent = mean(value))

Graph Interpretation: Earlier release date shows higher sentiment scores just above 0 compared to later release dates which are lower. This indicates that Taylor Swift used more positive language in her earlier albums, but overall her average language is either negative or close to average of negative and positive (0). You can also see that her album sales fluctuate, but the older albums with more positive language have a large dot, indicating that maybe her more positive music leads to more sales. This can explain why her sentiment fluctuates overtime as she may be changing her music sentiment based on sales.
